Funds are supposed to go to two (2) sources: the Local Housing Trust Fund (CBDG SHIP) and the other one to the State Housing Trust Fund (SAIL-State Apartment Incentive Loan). Bill after Bill has been passed by the State over the past couple decades.  All of these new laws that relate to land development have harmed local government's ability to regulate, guide, tax, and promote new development.  In many cases, the bills have only been passed for the benefit of specific companies.  Many other new laws mandated by the State have added administrative burdens on local governments by adding new layers of regulation; passing duties to local government employees that were once handled by the State; or by exempting developers of their obligations, leaving those obligations on the locality to correct.  In all cases, the State does not provide additional funding to localities, but rather, often reduces the amount of revenue localities can obtain from tax, proffers, fees, or other sources.

On the accessory dwelling unit question: we allow them by right in one plan area and will be evaluating a citywide program in the coming year. On the affordable housing contribution question, the affordable housing contributions are voluntary - a program worked out with developers -- and often they do make the voluntary contribution but sometimes they do not. The voluntary contributions are a main source of funds for the housing trust fund. We have a strong density bonus program for affordable housing. We do have a system for collecting developer contributions toward offsite infrastructure, but it is not through an impact fee. We have significantly increased densities for housing in the past 10-15; by tens of thousands of units.
